05399nam a22007575i 9780674258846DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742588467 a10.4159/97806742588462doi  a(DE-B1597)583145  a(OCoLC)1254026266  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF4755b.B87 2021 7aLAW0130002bisacsh04a342.7308/732231 aBurton, Orville Vernon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJustice Deferred :bRace and the Supreme Court /cOrville Vernon Burton, Armand Derfner. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote to the Reader -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Constitution, the Supreme Court, and the Road to Civil War -- t2 A New Birth of Freedom -- t3 The Supreme Court in Reconstruction -- t4 The Supreme Court and the Jim Crow Counterrevolution -- t5 Beginning the Long, Slow Turnaround -- t6 Breaking New Ground -- t7 The End of Separate but Equal -- t8 Opposing Forces: Massive Resistance and the Civil Rights Movement -- t9 A New Birth of Freedom, Again -- t10 Change in the Court -- t11 The War of Words: “Purpose” and “Effect” -- t12 Affirmative Action: Color Blind or Color Conscious -- t13 The Color of Criminal Justice -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex of Cases -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the first comprehensive accounting of the U.S. Supreme Court’s race-related jurisprudence, a distinguished historian and renowned civil rights lawyer scrutinize a legacy too often blighted by racial injustice. The Supreme Court is usually seen as protector of our liberties: it ended segregation, was a guarantor of fair trials, and safeguarded free speech and the vote. But this narrative derives mostly from a short period, from the 1930s to the early 1970s. Before then, the Court spent a century largely ignoring or suppressing basic rights, while the fifty years since 1970 have witnessed a mostly accelerating retreat from racial justice. From the Cherokee Trail of Tears to Brown v. Board of Education to the dismantling of the Voting Rights Act, historian Orville Vernon Burton and civil rights lawyer Armand Derfner shine a powerful light on the Court’s race record—a legacy at times uplifting, but more often distressing and sometimes disgraceful. For nearly a century, the Court ensured that the nineteenth-century Reconstruction amendments would not truly free and enfranchise African Americans. And the twenty-first century has seen a steady erosion of commitments to enforcing hard-won rights. Justice Deferred is the first book that comprehensively charts the Court’s race jurisprudence. Addressing nearly two hundred cases involving America’s racial minorities, the authors probe the parties involved, the justices’ reasoning, and the impact of individual rulings. We learn of heroes such as Thurgood Marshall; villains, including Roger Taney; and enigmas like Oliver Wendell Holmes and Hugo Black. Much of the fragility of civil rights in America is due to the Supreme Court, but as this sweeping history also reminds us, the justices still have the power to make good on the country’s promise of equal rights for all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistory. 0aCivil rightszUnited States. 0aRace discriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Civil Rights.2bisacsh  a13th Amendment.  a14th Amendment.  a15th Amendment.  aAfrican American.  aAmerican Indian.  aAsian-American.  aCivil Rights.  aConstitution.  aHispanic.  aJim Crow.